{
  "query": "How does the evidence for managing existing hedgerows for bats compare to that for planting new ones?",
  "relevant_summary": "The evidence for managing existing hedgerows for bats is limited but shows some positive effects, while there is no evidence available for planting new hedgerows specifically for bats. Two studies evaluated the effects of managing hedges to benefit bat populations, both conducted in the UK (Action 1943). One replicated, site comparison study found that hedges trimmed \u22653 years prior had more bat species recorded along them than hedges trimmed during the previous winter. Additionally, hedges trimmed \u22653 years prior had higher activity of two of eight bat species/species groups than hedges trimmed during the previous winter. However, one replicated, paired sites study found that pipistrelle activity did not differ between hedges managed for wildlife on agri-environment scheme farms and hedges on conventional farms (Action 1943). In stark contrast, no studies were found that evaluated the effects of planting new hedges on bat populations (Action 1942). Similarly, no studies were found that evaluated the effects of creating new unlit bat commuting routes using planting on bat populations (Action 2034). This represents a significant evidence gap, as there is currently no scientific basis for comparing the effectiveness of these two approaches for bat conservation.",
