{
  "query": "In the agricultural sector, what are the observed effects of organic farming systems compared to conventional farming on bat populations?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on twelve studies evaluating organic farming compared to conventional farming on bat populations (action 961), the effects are mixed. Regarding species diversity, five of seven studies found no difference in the number of bat species between organic and non-organic farms, while two studies found more bat species on organic farms. For bat abundance, five of nine studies found no difference in overall bat activity between organic and non-organic farms, while four studies found higher overall bat activity, bat feeding activity, Brazilian free-tailed bat activity, and activity of four of seven bat species on organic farms. Two UK studies found higher activity of Myotis species over water and rivers on organic farms, and one French study found higher activity for two of three bat species over organic fields compared to conventionally managed fields. Additionally, studies on reducing chemical inputs (action 2013) found that farms using few or no chemicals had different bat species compositions and higher diversity of insect-eating bat species compared to farms with high chemical inputs. Two studies showed farms or grasslands with few or no chemical inputs had higher overall bat activity than those using high chemical inputs. One study found great fruit-eating bats in chemical-free silvopastoral areas had higher body weights and body condition scores than those in conventional farming areas using chemicals.",
  "action_ids": [
    "961",
