{
  "query": "What design and placement factors influence the successful use of bat boxes by bats?",
  "relevant_summary": "Design factors that influence successful bat box use include color, size, material, and internal structure. Three studies found that bats used black bat boxes more than grey, white or wooden boxes (Action 1024). One of two studies found higher occupancy rates in larger bat boxes (Action 1024). Studies found varied results for materials: bats used both resin and wood cylindrical boxes, but resin boxes became occupied more quickly than wood boxes in one study, while another found higher occupancy rates in concrete than wooden boxes (Action 1024). Indiana bats used rocket boxes more than wooden boxes or bark-mimic roosts (Action 1024). Internal structure matters as more bats occupied boxes with two compartments than one compartment in the breeding season, bat breeding colonies occupied standard and four/five chamber boxes, and individuals occupied flat boxes (Action 1024). Bat boxes simulating tree trunks were used by 100% of bats in group sizes similar to natural roosts (Action 1024).\n\nPlacement factors include orientation, height, mounting location, and surrounding habitat. Three studies found that bat box orientation and/or the amount of exposure to sunlight affected bat occupancy, though one study found orientation did not have a significant effect (Action 1024). Two studies found that bat box height affected occupancy, while two other studies found no effect of height (Action 1024). Two studies found higher occupancy of bat boxes on buildings than on trees (Action 1024). Habitat influences occupancy as bat boxes were occupied more often in farm forestry sites than in native forest, higher occupancy occurred in pine relative to mixed deciduous stands, and higher occupancy was found in forest fragments than in pasture (Action 1024). Higher occupancy rates occurred in areas where bats were known to roost prior to installing bat boxes, and bat boxes were more likely to be occupied when a greater number were installed across a site (Action 1024). Temperature management also affects success, as one study found more bats in artificial roosts after they were modified to reduce internal roost temperatures (Action 2052).",
